I don't know how best to express my opinion to minimise the risk of a shitfight, but let's try.

This doesn't really convey to me anything more than most American popular media relating to 9/11, regarding the various inspirational stories that came out of it - which is fine, but fictional inspirational stories never live up to the emotional impact of real ones.

I would have novoted and left it at that, but I think it conveys a rather unhealthy stance on the event that is also common in popular media, namely trying to represent it as some sort of transformative moment of noble, heroic American glory. Without diminishing the presence of individual acts of heroism, I don't see the event itself as anything more than a disaster - a marker for 20 years of insanity, horrors and depravity - and the clockwork romanticisation of it every year leaves a bitter taste in my mouth.

I could be entirely projecting onto something that isn't there, though.







