I think pretending like it was some sort of triumphant stand against tyranny, or pretending like this article is trying to imply as much, is missing the mark pretty dramatically. This article is just about people helping people, and the spirit of collective self-sacrifice that comes with tragedy. I purposefully avoided trying to make any larger point here, because the larger story is not an encouraging one.

What is encouraging, I think, is moments of individual sacrifice - for total strangers, out of nothing more than kindred togetherness. That's why I wanted to write this, and that's what I think is the best story to tell.







