I wanted to explain why I downvoted this one because I think it's worth doing in this case. Aside from little things like the graphic at the start kind of just being there for no reason (aren't all SCP documents classified to some degree?), there's a major problem at the center of it that keeps bothering me. The anomaly is simple, yet manages to undercut the story it's trying to tell. By making the firefighter intangible and indefatigable it begs the question what is she sacrificing for other people?

If I were an anomalous entity that was immune to smoke inhalation and burns I'd probably be the best choice for a firefighter because it'd be pretty easy for me to go about a burning building helping people. I'll admit that the article does try to show her being run ragged by the sheer amount of people that need helping, but that seems to be the same problem one runs into with characters like Superman (impossible to defeat so the only problem is they can't be everywhere to help everyone) and then that comparison just makes me wonder about the whole concept.

I can fully understand the direction the story is going for and the necessity to keep the scope of the story small to avoid getting into politicised material, but I feel like the anomaly runs counter to the intention. I don't feel any sense of the message of shared sacrifice from it and it leaves me, personally, cold.







