I wouldn't say I was trying to tell a story about the anomalies' sacrifice, but explaining what I was trying to do might get into spoiler territory, so away we go.

spoilers

–block


The intent of emphasis here wasn't necessarily about the sacrifice of these two anomalous entities. Indeed - by their very nature they're incapable of doing so. They are more a defense mechanism; the spirit of New York made manifest to try and bring as many to safety as possible.

There's a line from a Springsteen song off the Rising album that goes . Ever since I heard that album and listened to that song, that line has stuck with me. What drives a person to forsake their own safety, even at the expense of their life, and climb those stairs? It was powerful imagery that I just couldn't shake.

These two, then, shouldn't be seen as some anomaly that draws people to safety and helps people who are in danger. Instead, they are manifested from that same sense of selfless devotion to one's fellow man - they wouldn't have existed in New York that day if it wasn't for the people of New York.

In that same sense, this is maybe the most real thing I've ever written here, because while I don't know if there were spirits in those towers, I do know that there was a spirit in the people rushing into them. That was real, and we all saw it.










